data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` tree no longer compiles. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All the `Expression.Parameter` / `Expression.Call` machinery is eliminated — EF Core 10 accepts `Action<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>>` directly.

---

### 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified / use full path

Two changes combine here:

- **Shared property names** (`ShippingAddress.Street` + `BillingAddress.Street`): columns are now auto-uniquified (e.g., `Street`, `Street1`). A migration will be generated to rename them.
- **Nested complex types** (`Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City`): column name changes from `BillingAddress_City` → `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (full path).

**Fix:** Pin the old column names explicitly so no migration rename occurs:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types, pin old names:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Alternatively, let EF generate the rename migration — just verify it matches your production schema.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. Fix:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
        DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)          // ← add this
    {
        // logCommandText contains redacted SQL (safe for logs)
        // command.CommandText has the actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update all method signatures on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
